The speaker feels that his friend's having all the
advantages is enough to make up for his own disadvantageous
position. (I do not see any implication that he gets
anything from his friend's wealth and so have paraphrased to
avoid it. Maybe he does, maybe he doesn't, but the poem does
not say so.)

Line 3, 'made lame'. Literal or metaphorical? I come down on
the side of metaphor for the following reason.
'Lame' plainly picks up 'decrepit' in line 1. (The weakness
of age typically shows itself in difficulty in getting
about: what is it that begins on four legs, continues on two
and ends on three?) Now, lines 1-2 are a simile. So it is
essential that the speaker is not in fact a decrepit father,
if a decrepit father is what he is compared with. Otherwise
the simile is pointless, mere repetition. So 'lame' is a
metaphor as in the line the commentators quote from the
Quarto of King Lear: 'A most poor man made lame by Fortune's
blows'.

Line 7: 'their'. I should have accepted Capell's 'thy'
against the Quarto. It is pointless to say that these things
'sit' without saying plainly where they sit.

Line 8, 'engrafted'. I take this to emphasise the firmness
and permanence of the graft. The fact that a graft depends
on the tree for nourishment seems not relevant.

Line 9, 'poor nor despised'. Burrow quotes Malone, from whom
I differ in fear and trembling. 'Lame' is explained by
referring back to lines 1 and 3. What explains 'poor' and
'despised'? I can see nothing in the poem. So it must be a
natural thing to say in the environment in which the poem
was written. First, it seems to me a natural thing for a
professional poet to say in addressing an aristocratic
patron. It does not quite say 'Please alleviate my poverty',
but it does not disown it. Secondly, the speaker is some
kind of version of the author and we know that actors were
often despised. So 'lame' here is a metaphor, explained by
lines 1 and 3, while 'poor nor despised' is meant literally,
if perhaps with some exaggeration.

Line 10. All commentators point out that here the shadow
creates the substance, which is the wrong way round for the
convention. That is purely a verbal effect: we have to
re-interpret the words 'shadow' and 'substance' to avoid
making the poet talk nonsense.

Line 13, 'Look what' is just a way of saying 'Whatever'. The
three phrases progress, using the words 'best ... best' and
'wish ... wish' to work up to the climax at the end of line
14.

