I'm trying to relate this poem back to the
discussion of whether 36 is connected to 33-35.

In 33-35, the addressee did something that caused
disgrace for the speaker.

In 36, it is unclear whether the &quot;blots&quot; that are
mentioned refer to the disgrace of 33-35, or whether they
are the personal shortcomings the speaker has already
mentioned - in 29, for instance.

Now we come to 37. Here, clearly, the shortcomings
of the speaker mentioned have nothing to do with the actions
of the addressee. 37 has nothing to do with 33-35. Agreed?
But what about 36? It seems to me that 37 supports the
argument that 36 is also unconnected to 33-35. In 36, the
poet finds private solace in the good reputation of the
addressee which heals his own &quot;bewailed guilt&quot;, while in 37
the addressee's beauty, birth, wealth and wit help satisfy
the speaker's personal shortcomings in those areas. In both
36 and 37, the speaker's relationship with the addressee is
of the 'what is yours is mine' variety. (Although you then
have to wonder why the speaker's bewailed guilt and poverty
are not then part of the addressee. But no matter.)

If the sonnets are a series of episodic scenes from
a relationship, then it seems to me that 33-35 are out of
place, and that 36 and 37 form a part of the scene outlined
in 29.

Or at least that's the way I see it now, before I've
read any of the commentaries.

- Gary Kosinsky

