I'm not sure it's as simple as that:

I make my loue ingrafted to this store:
So then I am not lame,poore, nor dispis'd,
Whilst that this shadow doth such substance giue,
That I in thy abundance am suffic'd,
And by a part of all thy glory liue:

I'm wondering if the &quot;shadow&quot; is the imagination, which makes the poet
whole; the inner man is/becomes more real, more substantial than his
appearance, a common theme in Shakespeare. Thus &quot;this shadow&quot; is related to
the addressee, to whom the poet is &quot;ingrafted&quot; and indebted for these
particular imaginings and feelings of wholeness, but not the addressee
himself.

Another way of interpreting it might be that &quot;the shadow&quot; is the inner man
himself, whole, rich, respected.

Lynne

