&gt; I'm still not sure what the speaker means by
&gt;&quot;shadow&quot;. Does he mean his image of the addressee gives him
&gt;satisfaction for his shortcomings?

"/>

I think 'this shadow' means the 'store' (line 8) which
contains beauty, birth, wealth, wit (line 5) and other
things like them. What makes it a shadow is that these are
all abstract nouns. They give weight ('substance') to the
speaker's own participation in the same store; they make him
significant in the world.

This is more far-fetched than I really like, but Shakespeare
often flies beyond the reach of those of us who like to keep
our feet on the ground. Here I think he is using 'shadow'
and 'substance' in a deliberately riddling way.

