Spenser in a letter to Gabriel Harvey and
dated from Leicester House In October
1579 says that Sidney and Dyer:
&quot; . . have proclaimed in their Areopagos
a general surceasing and silence of bald
rhymers, and also of the very best too;
instead whereof they have, by authority
of their whole Senate, prescribed certain
laws and rules of quantities of English
syllables for English verse; having had
thereof great practice, and drawn me to
their faction . .&quot;
(Ward, *Oxford*, p 175, quoting
Courthope, A History of English Poetry)

The famous 'tennis-court row' between
Sidney and Oxford appears to have taken
place in late August 1579. After Oxford
had called Sidney a 'puppy', Sidney
responded by alluding to the Earl's
incapacity to produce an heir. The poet
_may_ be regarding this as an allegation
of 'lameness' (of the middle leg) -- or of
'lameness' in a more general sense.

Walter Raleigh was appointed as an
intermediary by the Queen to sort out this
dispute. So it is possible that even as early
as this he was already her 'dearest spite' --
although I think it unlikely.

A well-known quote about Raleigh is
worth retailing, in passing:

&quot;Sir Walter Rawleigh,&quot; wrote Sir Robert Naunton, in what is
still the best thumb-nail sketch of Ralegh's career, &quot;was one,
that (it seems) Fortune had pickt out of purpose, of whom
to make an example, or to use as her Tennis-Ball, thereby to
shew what she could doe; for she tost him up of nothing,
and too and fro to greatnesse, and from thence down to little
more than to that wherein she found him, (A bare Gentleman). &quot;
(Winton, Raleigh, page 10)

Here a rough analogy is made by a
contemporary between the Queen and
'Fortune' -- and their joint treatment of
Raleigh

There is a further possible allusion in 'lame'.
In July 1578 during a royal progress to
Cambridge, Oxford had refused to dance
for some French diplomats representing
Alencon. The reasons are obscure, but
'lameness' would be an excuse (either at
the time or retrospectively), and there
MAY be a connection here -- although
I think it unlikely.

However, any and all of these are far
more likely than the kind of literal
'lameness' that Lynne and her type of
quasi-Strat so lamely imagine was in
the mind of our great poet.

