I've never seen such a complaint before but, in
fact, the requirement would seem about right to me.

We KNOW Edward de Vere, Walter Raleigh,
Philip Sidney, and other courtiers wrote sonnets.
It was the fashion of the day for ambitious
courtiers. And we also know to whom they
addressed most of their sonnets -- and it was
not to some anonymous 'fair youth'.

But such activity might as well be on a different
planet as far as the Stratman is concerned. It would
be like seeing a John Wayne or Roy Rogers character
go into a frontier bar, and instead of having a fist-
fight with the local baddies, settle their dispute by
means of a sonnet-writing competition -- with the
winner being judged by the local sheriff or the
blowsy barmaid.

It would be something out of Monty Python.
The idea is nuts -- as is the notion of the Stratman
writing sonnets to a 'Fair Youth'.

Paul.

